            "text": "*Proof.* By Theorem 4.3, the result holds for  $q \\ge 194$ . For  $q < 194$  and  $q \\equiv 1 \\pmod{6}$ , we first look at  $q = 7$  and  $q = 13$ . When  $q = 7$ , one has  $x^6 = 1$  for all  $x \\in \\mathbb{F}_7^{\\times}$ . But  $g^2 + g + 1 \\neq 0$  for any primitive root  $g$  of  $\\mathbb{F}_7$ . So it is not solvable in this case. For  $q = 13$ ,  $x^6 = \\pm 1$  for all  $x \\in \\mathbb{F}_{13}^{\\times}$ . It is easy to check that  $g^2X^6 + gY^6 + 1 = 0$  is not solvable for all primitive roots  $g = 2, 6, 7, 11$  of  $\\mathbb{F}_{13}$ . For the rest of cases that  $13 < q < 194$ , the following table gives a solution for some primitive root  $g$ :",
